# CONSULT-46 — Q3 DESIGN (Opus): the safest throttle for ClientInteriorLayoutManager::update()

Angle: assume we DECIDE to throttle. Design the SAFEST possible throttle. (Others judge if/value/risk.)
READ-ONLY analysis — no code modified.

================================================================================
## 0. Ground-truth I verified in the tree (these drive the whole design)
================================================================================

GT-1. `update()` is called **once per frame**, unconditionally, from `GroundScene.cpp:2006`
      (inside the per-frame draw/alter path). So "spread across frames" = "let successive
      `update()` calls each do a bounded slice." No new pump is needed.

GT-2. The cell-done flag is a single bool, set unconditionally at line :84 BEFORE the inner
      create loop (:103-128). `CellProperty.h:229  bool mutable m_appliedInteriorLayout;`
      get/set at `CellProperty.cpp:1256/1263`. set() only ever flips it to true; there is no
      "partial" state today.

GT-3. **CRITICAL — the flag self-clears on unload.**
      `CellProperty::removeFromWorld()` (`CellProperty.cpp:563-580`) does
      `m_appliedInteriorLayout = false;` at :579. Also ctor inits false (:358). So when a cell
      leaves the world (player leaves POB, LOD eviction, fast in/out), the next time it is
      visible+inWorld it is treated as fresh and re-applied from scratch. This is the safety
      anchor: **the engine already gives us a reliable "this cell must (re)start from object 0"
      signal for free** — no teardown hook to add.

GT-4. **The created objects are owned by the building, freed on building unload.**
      `TangibleObject::addClientOnlyInteriorLayoutObject` (:1080-1086) stores a
      `Watcher<Object>` in `m_clientOnlyInteriorLayoutObjectList`. On building teardown,
      `TangibleObject::removeFromWorld()` (:495-507) `delete`s every object in that list and
      frees the list. So the building, not the manager, owns lifetime. The manager holds **no**
      authoritative pointer to created objects.

GT-5. The work source each frame is `RenderWorld::getVisibleCells()`
      (`stdvector<const CellProperty*>` — RenderWorld.h:56/100), recomputed by the renderer.
      Pointers in it are only valid for the duration of one `update()` call. They are NOT safe
      to stash across frames (a cell can unload between frames).

GT-6. The per-cell guards that gate creation are all re-checkable every frame from the live
      cell pointer: `getOwner().isInWorld()` (:76), `getPortalProperty()` (:87),
      owner→asTangibleObject (:94), `tangibleObject->getInteriorLayout()` (:98). The layout
      reader is deterministic & ordered: `getNumberOfObjects(cellName)` and
      `getObjectTemplateName(cellName, i)` / `getTransform_o2p(cellName, i)` (:103-106) — index
      `i` is a stable, replayable cursor into the layout file.

================================================================================
## 1. Model choice: RESUME-INDEX vs PENDING-QUEUE  →  pick RESUME-INDEX (count-based)
================================================================================

### (b) PENDING-CREATE QUEUE — REJECT.
WorldSnapshot's queue (WorldSnapshot.cpp:914, `ms_maximumNumberOfCreatesPerFrame`) is safe ONLY
because its entries reference **stable buildout `Node*`** that outlive any frame. Our work items
would have to capture `CellProperty*` + `TangibleObject*` + a layout index. The instant a
building/cell unloads, every queued entry for it is a dangling `CellProperty*`/`TangibleObject*`.
To make a queue safe you must (i) get an unload notification to purge it, or (ii) Watcher-wrap
the pointers and null-check on dequeue. (i) violates the "don't touch teardown elsewhere"
constraint; (ii) is doable (`Watcher<TangibleObject>` + re-resolve cell by name each pop) but it
is strictly MORE state and MORE failure surface than necessary — and it still has to solve the
re-derivation problem to handle "cell unloaded then came back" without dup/miss. The queue buys
nothing here.

### (a) RESUME — ACCEPT, but in its safe-by-construction form: a per-cell PROGRESS COUNT
       stored ON THE CELL, never a cross-frame raw pointer.

Do not store "which cell + which index" in the manager (that re-introduces a stashed
`CellProperty*`). Instead store, **on each CellProperty**, the count of layout objects already
created for it: `m_interiorLayoutCreatedCount` (int, mutable, default 0). The manager keeps NO
cross-frame state at all. Each frame it re-derives 100% of its work from the live visible-cell
list (GT-5) and each cell's own progress count (GT-3/GT-4 guarantee that count is consistent
with reality because it tracks the same lifecycle as `m_appliedInteriorLayout`).

This is the WorldSnapshot insight (bounded creates/frame) re-expressed against UNSTABLE runtime
pointers by **never holding the pointer** — the count lives with the object whose lifetime
defines validity.

================================================================================
## 2. The design (safe-by-construction)
================================================================================

### Storage delta (minimal, on CellProperty — the lifecycle owner):
- Replace/augment the bool with a count. Simplest: keep `m_appliedInteriorLayout` semantics by
  deriving "applied == (createdCount == totalForCell)" — OR keep the bool AND add a count.
  RECOMMEND: keep the bool, add `int mutable m_interiorLayoutCreatedCount = 0;`.
  - Reset BOTH in `removeFromWorld()` (:579) — add one line next to the existing reset (this is
    the ONE byte of CellProperty change, and it sits literally beside an existing reset of the
    same concept, so it is in-scope and self-evidently correct).
  - Reset both in ctor (:358 already resets the bool; add the count = 0).
- DO NOT set the "applied" bool until the cell is FULLY done (this fixes the :84-too-early bug).

### New pseudocode for update() (replaces :62-130):

```
static int s_maxCreatesPerFrame = config("ClientGame/ClientInteriorLayoutManager",
                                          "maxInteriorCreatesPerFrame", 0);  // 0 = unlimited (old behavior)

void update():
    if (disableLazy || disableInteriorLayouts) return;

    int budget = (s_maxCreatesPerFrame > 0) ? s_maxCreatesPerFrame : INT_MAX;

    const CellPropertyList & cells = RenderWorld::getVisibleCells();   // live, this-frame only (GT-5)
    for i in 0..cells.size():
        cell = cells[i]
        if (!cell || cell == worldCell) continue
        if (!cell->getOwner().isInWorld()) continue          // (GT-6) re-checked every frame
        if (cell->getInteriorLayoutFullyApplied()) continue  // was getAppliedInteriorLayout()

        portal = cell->getPortalProperty(); if (!portal) { markFullyApplied(cell); continue }
        owner  = portal->getOwner()
        tang   = owner.asClientObject() ? owner.asClientObject()->asTangibleObject() : 0
        if (!tang) { markFullyApplied(cell); continue }
        layout = tang->getInteriorLayout(); if (!layout) { markFullyApplied(cell); continue }

        cellName = TemporaryCrcString(cell->getCellName(), true)
        total    = layout->getNumberOfObjects(cellName)

        start = cell->getInteriorLayoutCreatedCount()        // RESUME cursor (GT-2 cursor is stable)
        idx = start
        while (idx < total && budget > 0):
            createOneInteriorObject(layout, cellName, idx, cell, tang)   // = old :105-127 body
            ++idx
            --budget
            cell->setInteriorLayoutCreatedCount(idx)         // PERSIST progress after EACH create
                                                             //   (crash/early-out safe; never re-does idx)
        if (idx >= total):
            cell->setInteriorLayoutFullyApplied()            // mark done ONLY when complete (fixes :84)
        if (budget <= 0):
            break                                            // stop this frame; resume next frame
```

`createOneInteriorObject` is exactly the existing inner body (:105-127): createObject →
addClientOnlyInteriorLayoutObject → setParentCell → (portalTransitions off) setTransform →
addObjectNotifications → endBaselines → addToWorld. Including the failure branch (:126-127):
note that a `createObject`==null still consumes an index (++idx) so a bad template doesn't wedge
the cursor — matches old behavior of "skip and continue."

================================================================================
## 3. CORRECTNESS ARGUMENT (no-miss / no-dup / no-dangle)
================================================================================

Let, for a given live cell C with building B and layout L, `total(C)` = L->getNumberOfObjects(C)
(a pure function of the layout file, deterministic & order-stable — GT-6), and let
`created(C)` = C.m_interiorLayoutCreatedCount.

**Invariant I:** at the start of every `update()`, for every cell ever seen,
`created(C)` equals the number of layout objects of C currently live in B's
`m_clientOnlyInteriorLayoutObjectList`, AND those are exactly indices `[0, created(C))` of L.

- **Establishment:** ctor sets created=0 and the building list is empty → I holds. (GT-3/GT-4)
- **Preservation by a create step:** we call createOne(idx==created(C)) → push to B's list →
  THEN `++created(C)`. The created object corresponds to layout index `created(C)` before the
  increment. So the set of live objects becomes exactly `[0, created(C)+1)`. I preserved.
  Persisting AFTER the push (not before) is what makes a mid-loop early-out / crash safe: if we
  die between push and ++, worst case is created lags by one and that single object is re-created
  next frame — but see NO-DUP below for why even that can't double-add.
- **Preservation by unload:** B->removeFromWorld() deletes ALL objects in the list AND we reset
  created(C)=0 in CellProperty::removeFromWorld (GT-3 already fires for the cell; we add the
  count reset right beside it). Both sides snap to empty/0 together → I preserved. THIS is the
  no-dangle guarantee: the count and the object list are reset by the SAME lifecycle event, so
  the count can never out-live (or under-count) the objects.

**NO-MISS:** A cell is marked `FullyApplied` ONLY when `idx >= total` (loop ran the cursor to the
end). Until then it stays un-applied and is revisited every frame (it's still in
getVisibleCells while visible). Each frame advances the cursor by ≥0 and, whenever budget>0 and
work remains, by ≥1 (forward progress, see §4). So created(C) monotonically rises to total(C)
in finite frames, then FullyApplied latches. No index in [0,total) is ever skipped because the
loop is a contiguous `while (idx < total)` starting at exactly `created(C)`. ∎

**NO-DUP:** The only creator is the `idx` loop, which starts at `created(C)` and never revisits
an index < created(C) (created only increases while the cell stays in-world). The other path that
could create twice — flicker (cell drops out of visible list for a frame then returns) — does NOT
reset created(C): `m_appliedInteriorLayout`/count reset only on `removeFromWorld()` (a real
world-leave), NOT on mere invisibility. So a flicker just pauses progress; on return we resume at
created(C). And a true unload resets created→0 AND deletes the objects together (Invariant I), so
the post-reload pass re-creates [0,total) into a now-empty list — correct, not duplicate. ∎
(Contrast: the OLD code's bug surface — if you split the burst but kept the :84 early mark, a
flicker mid-burst would see AppliedInteriorLayout==true and MISS the tail. Our fix is to move the
mark to completion AND key resumption off the count, so flicker is miss-proof.)

**NO-DANGLE:** The manager stores ZERO cross-frame pointers. Every frame it re-acquires cell,
portal, owner, tangible, layout fresh from the live visible-cell list and re-runs the null guards
(GT-6). The only persisted datum is an int count living ON the cell, whose lifetime is the cell's
own. A queue of `CellProperty*`/`TangibleObject*` (model b) would dangle; a count cannot dangle.
∎

================================================================================
## 4. BUDGET: value, config knob, anti-starvation
================================================================================

- **Knob:** `ClientGame/ClientInteriorLayoutManager / maxInteriorCreatesPerFrame`, int, via the
  existing `ConfigFile::getKeyInt` pattern used at install() (the file already reads keys in this
  section — :44/:46). **Default 0 = unlimited = byte-for-byte old behavior** (zero-risk default;
  the throttle is opt-in until validated, then the cfg flips it on). This keeps the change inert
  for anyone who doesn't set the cfg and makes A/B trivial.
- **Recommended value:** start at **8–12 creates/frame.** Rationale: the cantina is the stress
  case; if the burst is ~N objects in one cell, a cap of ~10 spreads it over ceil(N/10) frames.
  At 30fps that's a few hundred ms of gentle fill instead of one hitch — below the perceptual
  hitch threshold while finishing the room in well under a second. Tune by measuring cantina N
  (the burst-quantification consultant owns that number; wire the knob so it's a one-line cfg
  change, no rebuild).
- **Anti-starvation / guaranteed forward progress:** budget is a per-FRAME cap, refreshed every
  frame; it is never carried/decremented across frames. As long as `maxInteriorCreatesPerFrame >= 1`
  (or 0=unlimited), every frame with remaining work creates ≥1 object → strictly monotonic
  created(C) → completion in ≤ ceil(total/cap) frames. There is no global queue that one cell can
  hog forever: the OUTER loop is over visible cells in renderer order, and budget is shared. To
  avoid one giant cell starving smaller ones in the same frame you could round-robin, but for the
  cantina (effectively one POB visible at a time) the simple shared-budget drain is fine and
  simpler — recommend NOT adding round-robin unless multi-POB starvation is observed. Guard
  against a pathological cfg of negative/zero meaning "never": treat `<=0` as unlimited (old
  behavior) so a typo can't wedge interiors to empty.

================================================================================
## 5. SMALLEST VIABLE DIFF SHAPE
================================================================================

Contained almost entirely to ClientInteriorLayoutManager.cpp, plus ~3 trivial lines in
CellProperty (the count field + its two resets, sitting beside identical existing resets).

A. **CellProperty.h** (1 line): add `int mutable m_interiorLayoutCreatedCount;` near :229.
   Optionally rename the bool concept to a helper, but keep the bool to minimize churn.
   Add inline accessors get/setInteriorLayoutCreatedCount (or reuse a small pair like the
   existing get/setAppliedInteriorLayout at :180-181).

B. **CellProperty.cpp** (3 lines):
   - :358 ctor — init `m_interiorLayoutCreatedCount(0)` in the init list.
   - :579 removeFromWorld — add `m_interiorLayoutCreatedCount = 0;` directly beside the existing
     `m_appliedInteriorLayout = false;` (SAME lifecycle event → keeps Invariant I; this is the
     no-dangle linchpin and is self-evidently in scope because it mirrors the line above it).
   - implement the count accessors (or make them inline in the header → 0 cpp lines).
   ⚠ CellProperty.h is a shared header consumed by plugins → adding a data member changes the
   struct → ABI cascade (per AGENTS.md shared-header trap). Adding an int to CellProperty triggers
   "rebuild ALL plugin .vcxprojs (gl05/06/07/11)", not just SwgClient. This is the one cross-file
   cost; it is mechanical (full 5-target build) but must be honored or you get a deterministic
   boot crash. (If you want to AVOID even that: store the count in a manager-side
   `std::map<const CellProperty*, int>` keyed by pointer — but then YOU must purge it on unload,
   which reintroduces the teardown-hook dependency and a stale-key hazard. NOT recommended; the
   on-cell int is strictly safer. The ABI rebuild is the cheaper price.)

C. **ClientInteriorLayoutManager.cpp** (the substantive change, self-contained):
   - install() (:44 area): read `maxInteriorCreatesPerFrame` (int) into a file-static.
   - update() (:62-130): replace the inner unconditional full-loop with the budgeted resume loop
     from §2. Move the "mark applied" from before the loop (:84) to AFTER completion. Factor the
     :105-127 body into a small local `createOneInteriorObject` helper (or inline it; the loop
     change is the same either way). NO other functions touched. `applyInteriorLayout` (:134, the
     eager non-lazy path) is left ENTIRELY untouched — it isn't the per-frame burst path.

D. **Config (stage cfg)**: add `maxInteriorCreatesPerFrame=10` under
   `[ClientGame/ClientInteriorLayoutManager]` in client_d.cfg / client.cfg (BOM-safe edit only).
   With the 0-default, this cfg line is the entire "turn it on" surface; remove it to revert.

Net: ~1 header line (+inline accessors), ~3 CellProperty.cpp lines, one rewritten loop +
one config read in the manager, one cfg line. No teardown hook added anywhere. No new container.
No cross-frame pointer. The only non-local cost is the mandatory plugin ABI rebuild from touching
CellProperty.h.

================================================================================
## 6. One-paragraph recommendation (design verdict, scoped to Q3)
================================================================================

Use a **count-based resume cursor stored on CellProperty**, not a pending-create queue and not a
manager-side stashed pointer. It is safe BY CONSTRUCTION because (1) the manager holds no
cross-frame pointer and re-derives all work each frame from the live visible-cell list + per-cell
re-checked guards (no-dangle); (2) the resume cursor and the created-object list are reset by the
SAME lifecycle event — CellProperty/TangibleObject::removeFromWorld — so they can never disagree
(no-dangle/no-dup across unload+reload); (3) flicker (mere invisibility) does NOT reset the
cursor, and the "applied" latch moves to LOOP COMPLETION, so a paused burst resumes exactly where
it stopped (no-miss, no-dup); (4) a per-frame cap refreshed every frame with `>=1` guarantees
monotonic forward progress to completion (no-starve). Budget knob
`maxInteriorCreatesPerFrame`, default 0 = unlimited (inert/old behavior), recommend 8–12 once the
cantina object count is known. The diff is contained to the manager + three CellProperty lines;
the only non-local cost is the shared-header ABI plugin rebuild from adding the int.
